ondition that was already present when my upgrade task began, since the cluster was already at v24.1.0 when I started.\n\nThe core issue is that node 1 can't increment its epoch in the liveness table due to slow heartbeats, which prevents it from acquiring leases. Since nodes 0 and 2 are healthy and form a quorum, the oracle is functioning, but I need all three nodes operational. The node is likely struggling with resource constraints in the kind cluster environment, so I should consider either waiting for recovery or deleting the pod to force a restart. wait and monitor whether the node recovers on its own, since the readiness probe has been consistently failing for several minutes now. I'm also considering whether restarting the pod might help the node rejoin the cluster, though there's a timing risk. Let me look more closely at whether there's background migration work happening from the cluster version finalization that might be blocking the node's liveness checks.\n\nLooking back at the timeline, stage_01 deployed a fresh v24.1.0 cluster with TLS enabled, and the precondition logs for stage_02 show 4 running pods. The current state is that two nodes are healthy while crdb-cluster-1 is struggling with liveness, likely due to either the upgrade finalization process triggering migrations or resource constraints in the kind cluster. The v23.2 to v24.1 finalization involves running background migrations that can be resource-intensive and temporarily impact node performance. I should verify whether the binary upgrade and version finalization have already completed, since the cluster appears to already be at v24.1.0 with the preserve_downgrade_option cleared.\n\nLooking at the pod events, crdb-cluster-1 has been unhealthy since it started 7 minutes ago—the readiness probe failures span the entire pod lifetime, so this is a pre-existing issue in the inherited environment. My verification checks 1, 2, 3, and 5 are passing, but I need to address the node health issue by 