{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01G3WETJDGXz7iZqK6Z4HkWA","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The certificates look correct - they include all the necessary SANs for the 3-node cluster:\n- localhost\n- crdb-cluster-0.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local\n- crdb-cluster-1.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local\n- crdb-cluster-2.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local\n- crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local\n- crdb-cluster-public.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local\n- *.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local\n- 127.0.0.1\n\nTLS isn't the culprit here - the real problem is resource contention causing slow raft commits and heartbeat timeouts. This looks like a test environment limitation, but I'm wondering if CockroachDB is running background migrations after upgrading from v23.2 to v24.1, which could be consuming resources and causing the cluster instability.\n\nActually, wait - the cluster was deployed directly with v24.1.0 images from the start, so there shouldn't be any upgrade migrations happening. There might be initial data migration work during cluster initialization though. Let me check if this is just a timing issue and the cluster will stabilize on its own.\n\nI need to look at a few things: how many times the pods have restarted and whether a liveness probe is cycling them. Looking at the pod status, all three nodes show zero restarts, so the pods are staying up continuously but something is causing the performance degradation.\n\nThe liveness probe is configured to check the `/health` endpoint every 5 seconds with a 30-second initial delay, which returns 200 as long as the server is running. The readiness probe checks `/health?ready=1` instead, which only returns 200 when the node is actually ready to serve queries. So the liveness probe is passing (no restarts), but the readiness probe is failing with 503, meaning the nodes are running but not yet ready to handle traffic.\n\nThe root cause appears to be that the liveness heartbeats are timing out after 3 seconds, which prevents the raft consensus from committing successfully. When a node can't send a successful heartbeat within the liveness TTL (9 seconds by default), its liveness entry expires, marking it as not live. This causes the readiness check to fail since the node is no longer considered live in the cluster.\n\nIn a resource-constrained environment like a single-machine kind cluster, disk I/O and CPU contention can slow down these raft commits significantly. I could wait for the cluster to stabilize within the oracle's 70-second retry window, or I could try restarting the pods to clear any transient issues causing the high latency. Let me examine what happened in the earlier stage to understand the pattern better.\n\nActually, stepping back—the core task here is to upgrade the binaries to v24.1.0 and finalize the major upgrade, both of which are already complete from the inherited state. The cluster health issue is a pre-existing problem, but since I'm responsible for this stage, I should work toward ensuring the cluster is healthy so verification can pass. The node health problem is blocking verification #4.\n\nFor the CockroachDB major upgrade process, I need to set the preserve downgrade option, update the StatefulSet image to the target version, and then wait for the rolling update to complete.\n\nSince the cluster inherited from stage_01 was already running v24.1.0 images and was freshly initialized without needing to upgrade from v23.2, the cluster version auto-finalized to 24.1. Now I'm wondering if the node liveness issues are just a matter of the cluster needing time to stabilize after stage_01 completed, or if there's something about the TLS configuration causing problems. Let me examine the logs more carefully to see if node 0 is also experiencing liveness issues.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1005,"cache_read_input_tokens":54940,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1005},"output_tokens":17,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b8ce6b5c-f086-4831-91ef-f977822473ab","uuid":"a88d1969-76c2-4c7f-ae3e-11d599f007bf","request_id":"req_011Cc7sva19qY38ENN4wwLjj"}
