{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DZESjonGo45HC986jF9vsA","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I don't see a direct setting for the node liveness heartbeat timeout. But I can try to increase the `server.time_until_store_dead` to give nodes more time before being declared dead. But this might not help with the heartbeat operation timeout.\n\nLet me look for the node liveness heartbeat interval setting.\n\nActually, looking at the CockroachDB v24.1 settings, the node liveness heartbeat has a default timeout of 3s (as seen in the logs) and a default interval of 4.5s. These are compile-time constants and not cluster settings.\n\nWait - actually there might be a way. Looking at CRDB's settings:\nThe real question is whether the cluster is actually broken or still functional. Node 3 appears consistently healthy, while nodes 1 and 2 are flaky—their raft commits are taking 1-17 seconds, which exceeds the 3-second heartbeat timeout, causing liveness entries to expire when commits run long. But the cluster seems to still be operational despite this. Looking at this slow raft commit log entry, the 1.76 second commit-wait is the real bottleneck—that's the time waiting for raft to apply the write. With all three nodes running on the same physical machine competing for the same disk, I'm likely hitting disk I/O contention. The semaphore wait is negligible, so it's not a scheduling issue. This explains why node 0's liveness heartbeats are timing out—the liveness range writes are getting stuck behind slow disk operations.\n\nI could try reducing resource requirements or disabling background jobs to lower disk pressure, but that's treating the symptom. Looking back at the precondition note, this is actually a workflow ordering problem—the test case explicitly warns that chaining stages without proper cluster state management creates this exact scenario. Stage_01 deployed a v24.1.0 cluster, and the subsequent stages are hitting performance issues because the cluster state wasn't properly prepared for the upgrade sequence.\n\nThe node health fluctuations seem transient—all nodes were live earlier, then degraded, which suggests the kind cluster is cycling between available and unavailable as resource contention varies. I should wait for the oracle's retry window to stabilize and check the node status again.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":300,"cache_read_input_tokens":60442,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":300},"output_tokens":20,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b8ce6b5c-f086-4831-91ef-f977822473ab","uuid":"a968b6ad-3b87-46fc-98d5-4ebc17e21f1d","request_id":"req_011Cc7t2UEoCgJDfCHBgyHQ1"}
